arch:property.oc:show_val: This soil locus appears to have been deposited during or shortly after the collapse event. The greatest depth for the deposit is where it flanks the Collapse Locus 4. From this collapse pile, it slopes outward toward the north and south, intermixing with the Locus 12 fill. The soils range from silt to granular, with a Munsell Color range between 5 YR 6/3 (Light Reddish Brown) and 5/3 (Reddish Brown). The material cultural remains included pottery, glass, a single coin, an iron harness loop, and many fragments of marble opus sectile.
3.70 m north south-by-5.65 m east west.

Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of the West Colonnade directly on top of the Hexagonal Pavement and into the West Cryptoporticus. The accumulation of early debris during this phase contains large amounts of architectural elements mixed with fill and sedimentation washed over the east perimeter wall. Some collapse is also seen in the south of the East Triple Colonnade.
Soil Deposit Above Terracotta Tile Subfloor (Locus 17)
